namaste,

 

There have a been a lot of replie=
s to this question. I wanted to share a suggestion that works along with an=
y of these.

 

In all vaidika karmas, there is a procedure called "pratisa=
ra-bandha". This is a raksha bandhana where a cotton thread (optimally made=
 of 9 strands) is energized with mantras and then worn around the wrist so =
that a little of the mantra shakti stays with you. A kalasha is established=
, with some vibhuti and a cotton thread placed to it's north. Then, Varuna =
is invoked in the kalasha, and then a number of vedic mantras are recited. =
At the end, we pray to Varuna once again, and then sprinkle the water from =
the kalasha on the yajamana and the cotton thread. The cotton thread is the=
n worn on the wrist (right hand for men, left hand for women) as an amulet,=
 and the vibhuti is worn on the forehead.

 

The vaidika procedure specifi=
es particular sets of mantras. In the bodhayana tradition, this starts with=
 the rAkshoghnam (something to destroy rAkshasas). However, you may use som=
e other mantra in it's place. If you are using the hanuman chalisa, as Nara=
simha suggested, you can chant that mantra a number of times, and then wear=
 the thread and vibhuti. Or, you could follow the Satayanarayana puja manua=
l with the cotton thread and vibhuti near by, and then sprinkle the thread =
with water and then wear it and the vibhuti. You could even put a pot of wa=
ter, think of Varuna, then do a bunch of bhajans, and then wear the thread =
and sprinkle the water on the area where you will be sleeping. The principl=
e is the same. 

 

The procedure for "pratisarabandha" specifically mentio=
ns disturbed sleep as an application.

 

sasneham,

 

    ajit

 

 

